=== PGlite Compatibility Audit for Database Migration ===

Generated: 2026-05-28T18:19:00Z

1. PACKAGE: @electric-sql/pglite
   Latest version: 0.4.6
   Status: Alpha (labeled "alpha" in README)
   Description: WASM Postgres build packaged into a TypeScript client library.
                Runs Postgres in browser, Node.js, Bun, and Deno.
                Only 3.7 MB gzipped.
   License: Apache 2.0 / PostgreSQL License (dual)
   Total versions on npm: 69

2. DRIZZLE ORM PGLITE ADAPTER: EXISTS
   drizzle-orm latest version: 0.45.2
   Exports found:
     - drizzle-orm/pglite          (entry point)
     - drizzle-orm/pglite/driver   (driver implementation)
     - drizzle-orm/pglite/session  (session layer)
     - drizzle-orm/pglite/migrator (migration support)
   Full ORM adapter support confirmed. PgliteSession, PgliteTransaction,
   PglitePreparedQuery all present.

3. TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL (REPEATABLE READ): SUPPORTED
   PGlite's transaction() method simply issues "BEGIN", "COMMIT", and "ROLLBACK"
   SQL commands via the Postgres wire protocol. Since PGlite runs a real Postgres
   engine in WASM, all standard Postgres SQL features are inherited:
   - Users can run "BEGIN TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL REPEATABLE READ" directly
     via the raw exec() method.
   - Drizzle ORM via PgTransactionConfig supports isolationLevel with values:
     'read uncommitted', 'read committed', 'repeatable read', 'serializable'.
     The adapter calls "SET TRANSACTION ISOLATION LEVEL <level>" on the inner
     PGlite transaction.
   - PgTransactionConfig also supports accessMode and deferrable options.
   Caveat: PGlite is single-user/single-connection. REPEATABLE READ technically
   works but has no concurrent transactions to isolate against. It may still be
   useful for read-consistency within a single transaction.

4. SELECT FOR UPDATE: SUPPORTED
   Since PGlite passes raw SQL to the Postgres engine, "SELECT ... FOR UPDATE"
   is fully supported at the SQL level. Drizzle ORM supports it via the
   .$forUpdate() query modifier on prepared statements.
   Caveat: Single-user mode means FOR UPDATE has no concurrent writers to block,
   but it operates correctly when present. If migrating to PGlite as an embedded
   Postgres (replacing SQLite), FOR UPDATE works but is effectively a no-op
   within single-connection usage.

5. KEY LIMITATIONS
   - Single user/connection: PGlite cannot handle concurrent connections.
     All queries are serialized through a JS-level mutex (#queryMutex and
     #transactionMutex in base.ts).
   - WASM-bound: Data is in-memory or persisted to indexedDB/filesystem,
     not a remote Postgres server.
   - Alpha status: Package is pre-1.0, API may change.
   - Only 3.7 MB gzipped WASM binary — supports many Postgres extensions
     (pgvector, etc.) but may not support all Postgres 16 features.

6. MIGRATION FEASIBILITY
   FEASIBLE with caveats:
   - drizzle-orm/pglite provides a drop-in adapter for existing Drizzle schema
     definitions (pg-core types).
   - SQLite types map directly: text() -> text(), integer() -> integer(),
     real() -> double precision(), text({mode:'json'}) -> jsonb(),
     integer({mode:'boolean'}) -> boolean()
   - $default and $onUpdate work identically in pg-core.
   - Data migration needed for json columns: existing SQLite TEXT columns with
     JSON content must be cast to Postgres jsonb type in the migration SQL.
   - Primary concern: single-user limitation means PGlite is not a replacement
     for multi-connection access patterns. Evaluate whether the OpenCode desktop
     app requires concurrent database access.

Summary: PGlite + drizzle-orm/pglite provides a viable path for SQLite-to-Postgres
migration on the desktop, with full Drizzle ORM support including transactions,
isolation levels, and prepared statements. The main tradeoff is the single-user
limitation inherent to the WASM Postgres architecture.
